'''James Carroll''' (December 2, 1791 &ndash; January 16, 1873) was born in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]. He graduated from [[St. Mary's Seminary and University|St. Mary's College]] in Baltimore in 1808. Carroll studied law, but did not practice. He settled on a farm on the [[West River (Maryland)|West River]], but later moved back to Baltimore. His reputation was improved when he became judge of the orphans' court and a trustee of the poor. He served as a director of the [[Baltimore & Ohio Railroad]] and the [[Chesapeake and Ohio Canal|Chesapeake & Ohio Canal Company]].

[[Image:Carroll Vault.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Carroll Vault]]
Carroll was elected a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[26th United States Congress|Twenty-Sixth United States Congress]] to represent [[Maryland's 4th congressional district|Maryland's Fourth District]]. He took seat in 1839, but had lost reelection and left in 1841. Carroll ran for [[Governor of Maryland]] in 1844, winning his party's nomination, but lost in the general election to [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] [[Thomas Pratt (Maryland politician)|Thomas G. Pratt]] by a margin of a mere 548 votes. He retired and died on January 16, 1873. He is interred in the Carroll vault in [[Old Saint Paul's Cemetery]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]].

He was a member of the [[Carroll family]].

