{{Infobox person | name = Kwon Hyuk-Bin | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = [[Seoul]], South Korea | nationality = South Korean | education = | occupation = Chairman, [[Smilegate]] | salary = | religion = | children = | parents = | relatives = | website = | restingplace = | ethnicity = | alma mater = [[Sogang University]] | known for = | networth = [[United States dollar|$]]5.9 billion (Feb 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/kwon-hyuk-bin/?list=korea-billionaires|title=Kwon Hyuk-Bin|publisher=}}</ref> | spouse = | other_names = }}
'''Kwon Hyuk-Bin''' is a billionaire Korean businessman who co-founded Korea's third largest gaming company, [[Smilegate]], maker of the popular [[CrossFire (video game)|CrossFire]] games. CrossFire has gone on to become the most popular [[first person shooter]] game in history. He owns 100% of [[Smilegate]] Holdings, which he founded in 2002.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gracechung/2015/09/23/online-hit-game-crossfire-mints-south-koreas-richest-self-made-billionaire/#6ed764927d18|title=Online Hit Game CrossFire Mints South Korea's Richest Self-Made Billionaire|first=Grace|last=Chung|publisher=}}</ref>
==Education and Career== Kwon holds an electrical engineering degree from [[Sogang University]]. After a failed education startup, 4Csof, Kwon turned down a software position at [[Samsung]] to pursue his goal of developing video games. He partnered with [[Tencent]] to break into the Chinese market.<ref name="auto"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/people_detail.php?q=Kwon+Hyuk-bin&mode=rich&num=6|title=THE INVESTOR|website=www.theinvestor.co.kr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20161222000337|title=[Super Rich] Seven numbers to explain self-made billionaire owner of Smilegate|first=The Korea|last=Herald|date=22 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref>
==Philanthropy== Kwon has been involved in starting Orange Farm, South Korea's largest private incubator and has donated over $5 million to building schools in Vietnam and China.<ref name="auto"/> He has also contributed over $2 million to his alma mater at [[Sogang University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wealthx.com/dossier/hyuk-bin-kwon/< |title=Bio|website=wealthx.com}}</ref>
