{{BLP sources|date=November 2017}}

[[File:Markus headshot.png|thumb|Markus Grompe]]'''Markus Grompe''' is a professor of Pediatrics{{when|date=December 2018}}, director of the Papé Family Pediatric Institute and the Oregon Stem Cell Center, practicing physician at [[Oregon Health & Science University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/xd/health/services/providers/index.cfm?personID=283|title=Health Care provider Markus Grompe, M.D. - OHSU Health Care|website=Oregon Health & Science University}}</ref>. He also  holds the Ray Hickey Endowed Chair at [[Doernbecher Children's Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/xd/about/dchf/about/news_06-23-08_grompe_pape.cfm|title=Grompe appointed chair|website=Oregon Health & Science University}}</ref> 

Grompe is a specialist in  hepatology and stem cell biology, and is known for the development of the "Fah mouse model", a [[Genetically modified mouse|transgenic mouse]] with an inactivating mutation ([[exon]] 5 deletion) in sequence encoding [[fumarylacetoacetate hydrolase]] (''Fah'').<ref>Grompe et al., Genes Dev. 1993 Dec 7(12A):2298-307</ref> This mouse strain has been a useful model of [[Type I tyrosinemia]], a human genetic disease caused by inactivating mutations in the ''Fah'' gene. The mice have been used to model diseases such as [[malaria]] and to optimize human gene therapy strategies 

Dr. Grompe has made major contributions to the study of [[Fanconi Anemia]]. His contributions to the study of this rare hematological deficiency has helped to reveal the contributions of the FANC protein complexes associated with the repair of double-stranded breaks in genomic DNA.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}

Markus Grompe is the founder of and scientific consultant for Yecuris Inc that distributes mice with "humanized" livers to pharmaceutical and biotech companies for pre-clinical research in infectious liver diseases, liver gene therapy, and drug metabolism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yecuris.com/company.html|title=company|website=www.yecuris.com}}</ref>

