{{Refimprove|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox casino | casino = The Mint | image = Las Vegas - Mint.jpg | image_size = 250px | image_caption = | address = 100 [[Fremont Street]] | location = [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], United States | architect = [[Zick & Sharp]] (casino), [[Yesco]] (neon sign), [[Martin Stern]] (hotel tower) | attractions= | rooms= | space_gaming = | shows = | notable_restaurants = | names_pre = | date_opened = 1957 | date_closed = {{end date and age|1988}} | renovations = 1965 | casino_type = Land-based | owner =Del Webb }}
'''The Mint Las Vegas''' was a hotel and casino in downtown [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]].
The Mint was the sponsor of the [[Mint 400]], the largest [[Off-roading|off road]] race from the mid-1960s to the mid-1980s.
The Mint was made famous (or infamous) as the first night's stay in [[Hunter S. Thompson]] and [[Oscar Zeta Acosta|Oscar Acosta]]'s legendary 1971 weekend trip to Las Vegas, immortalized in Thompson's novel ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas]].''
== History == The Mint opened in 1957.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.earlyvegas.com/downtown.html|title=Old Downtown Vegas |author= |date= |work= |publisher=earlyvegas.com |accessdate=2009-12-07}}</ref> [[Milton Prell]], who also owned the [[Sahara Hotel and Casino]] and the [[Aladdin, Las Vegas|Aladdin Hotel and Casino]] on the [[Las Vegas Strip]], was one of the original owners of The Mint. Prell and his associates had engaged a firm to use a computer to come up with a list of possible names for this new addition to downtown Las Vegas. They had been working late into the night in Prell's home, when his wife Debbie came into the room and suggested the place be named The Mint.
[[Del Webb]] assumed ownership around 1961 when he acquired other properties of Milton Prell.
On April 6, 1962, Sahara-Nevada Corporation – the operating group of the Sahara and Mint – announced plans for a 22-story hotel skyscraper addition to the Mint. The addition was expected to be completed within 16 months, at a cost of $5 million. The addition would be built on the Mint's north parking lot, and was to include 300 additional hotel rooms and suites. A six-story, {{convert|210000|sqft|abbr=on}} parking garage would be connected to the new hotel building, and would include more than 550 parking spaces.<ref>{{cite news|title=Skyscraper Hotel To Be Erected (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-apr-07-1962-p-1/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 7, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Skyscraper Hotel To Be Erected (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-apr-07-1962-p-6/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 7, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com|subscription=yes}}</ref> In May 1962, the city planned to review the permit for the new tower.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=City to Review Permit For Mint Tower|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-may-09-1962-p-10/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 9, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com|subscription=yes}}</ref> A [[groundbreaking]] ceremony was held for the tower in July 1962.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Mint Goes Up 22 Stories On Fremont St|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-jul-22-1962-p-45/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 22, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com|subscription=yes}}</ref>
Construction was still ongoing in July 1964, at which point the tower was planned to include 24 floors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wade|first=Dell|title=Parade of Progress|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-jul-26-1964-p-25/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 26, 1964|via=NewspaperArchive.com|subscription=yes}}</ref> Construction reached the 24th floor at the end of the year, with plans for an additional four floors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wade|first=Dell|title=Year of Progress, Recession, Plans|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-03-1965-425820/|accessdate=December 8, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 3, 1965|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The hotel tower was ultimately built with 26 stories, and was [[topped out]] on March 20, 1965, with plans to open later that month.<ref name=Topped/> The new tower stood {{convert|290|ft|abbr=on}}, and was one of the [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|tallest buildings in the state]] at the time, ranking only behind [[The Landmark Hotel and Casino]], which stood {{convert|297|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower May Finally Have Owner|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-18-1966-420724/|accessdate=December 8, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 18, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Talk in Progress|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-26-1966-420776/|accessdate=December 8, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Renovations were also done to the existing building, which included work to the Merri Mint Theatre, and expanded dining areas.<ref name=Topped>{{cite news|title=New Mint Hotel 'Topped Off'|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-21-1965-426931/|accessdate=December 8, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 21, 1965|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>
In 1988, The Mint was sold and became part of [[Binion's Horseshoe]].
==Shows== [[Patsy Cline]] performed at the Mint Casino's "Merri-Mint Theater" from November 23 - December 28, 1962, three months before her fatal plane crash. She appeared with [[Tompall & the Glaser Brothers]], and at one point developed "Vegas Throat" due to the dry desert heat. For several shows Patsy [[Lip sync|lip-synched]] to her records. [[The Wilburn Brothers]], with [[Loretta Lynn]] as part of their act, played the Merri-Mint for a couple of nights in October 1962. According to author Larry Jordan, in his book "[[Jim Reeves]]: His Untold Story," Reeves also played at the Mint Casino in the early-1960s. Peter Urquidi, "Man of Many Sounds", played the Top of the Mint for more than a decade until the early-1970s. Upstairs in the lounge was the Johnny Elvis Foster show ''For The Love Of Elvis''. The Memphis Sound also played at the Mint<!-- Needs clarification: "for 3 months from February 1978 though May 1981" -->. [[Sidney Fields]] of [[Abbott and Costello]] fame appeared on the same bill in a comedy act.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}
==Film history == The casino appears in the 1964 film ''[[Viva Las Vegas]]'' and in the 1971 [[James Bond]] film ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]''. The Mint can be seen in the background toward the end of the 1984 film ''[[Starman (film)|Starman]]''. The casino can also be seen several times towards the end of the 1987 [[U2]] [[music video]] "[[I Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For]]", which was filmed entirely on [[Fremont Street]]. A computer-generated reconstruction of the casino can be seen in the 1998 film ''[[Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (film)|Fear and Loathing In Las Vegas]]''. The Mint is also seen in music videos by [[Panic! at the Disco]] from their 2013 album, ''[[Too Weird to Live, Too Rare to Die!]]''
